# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: do-it-yourself-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After Reddit was sold to Condé Nast Publications in 2006, Swartz became more involved in activism, helping launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee in 2009.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2010, he became a research fellow at Harvard University's Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption, directed by Lawrence Lessig.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He founded the online group Demand Progress, known for its campaign against the Stop Online Piracy Act.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Federal prosecutors, led by Carmen Ortiz, charged him with two counts of wire fraud and eleven violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, carrying a cumulative maximum penalty of $1 million in fines, 35 years in prison, asset forfeiture, restitution, and supervised release.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz declined a plea bargain under which he would have served six months in federal prison.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Two days after the prosecution rejected a counter-offer by Swartz, he was found dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was inducted posthumously into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Aaron Hillel Swartz was born in Highland Park, 25 miles (40 kilometers) north of Chicago, to a Jewish family.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He was the eldest child of Susan and Robert Swartz and brother to Noah and Ben Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] His father founded the software firm Mark Williams Company.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] At an early age, Swartz immersed himself in the study of computers, programming, the Internet, and Internet culture.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He attended North Shore Country Day School, a small private school near Chicago, until ninth grade, when he left high school and enrolled in courses at Lake Forest College.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 1999, at age 12, he created the website The Info Network, a user-generated encyclopedia.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The site won the ArsDigita Prize, given to young people who create "useful, educational, and collaborative" noncommercial websites, and led to early recognition of Swartz's nascent talent in coding.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] At age 14, he became a member of the working group that authored the RSS 1.0 web syndication specification.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A year later, he became involved in the Creative Commons organization.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2004, he enrolled at Stanford University but left the school after his first year.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] During Swartz's first year at Stanford, he applied to Y Combinator's first Summer Founders Program, proposing to work on a startup called Infogami, a flexible content management system designed to create rich and visually interesting websites or a form of wiki for structured data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After working on it with co-founder Simon Carstensen over the summer of 2005, Swartz opted not to return to Stanford, choosing instead to continue to develop and seek funding for Infogami.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] As part of his work on Infogami, Swartz created the web.py web application framework because he was unhappy with other available systems in the Python programming language.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In the early fall of 2005, he worked with his fellow co-founders of another nascent Y Combinator firm, Reddit, to rewrite its Lisp codebase using Python and web.py.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Although Infogami's platform was abandoned after Not a Bug was acquired, Infogami's software was used to support the Internet Archive's Open Library project and the web.py web framework was used as the basis for many other projects by Swartz and many others.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] When Infogami failed to find further funding, Y Combinator organizers suggested Infogami merge with Reddit, which it did in November 2005, creating a new firm, Not a Bug, devoted to promoting both products.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] As a result, Swartz was given the title of co-founder of Reddit.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Although both projects initially struggled, Reddit made large gains in popularity in 2005–2006.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In October 2006, based largely on Reddit's success, Not a Bug was acquired by Condé Nast Publications, owner of *Wired* magazine.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz moved with his company to San Francisco to continue to work on Reddit for *Wired*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He found corporate office life uncongenial and in January 2007 was asked to resign from the company.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In September 2007, he joined Infogami co-founder Simon Carstensen to launch a new firm, Jottit, in another attempt to create a Markdown-driven content management system in Python.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz founded Watchdog.net, "the good government site with teeth", to aggregate and visualize data about politicians.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] That year, he wrote a widely circulated *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On December 27, 2010, he filed a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to learn about the treatment of Chelsea Manning, alleged source for WikiLeaks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] His activism has been praised by digital rights groups such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz downloaded about 2.7 million federal court documents stored in the PACER (Public Access to Court Electronic Records) database managed by the Administrative Office of the United States Courts.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The *Huffington Post* characterized his actions this way: "Swartz downloaded public court documents from the PACER system in an effort to make them available outside of the expensive service.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] PACER was charging eight cents per page for information that Carl Malamud, who founded the nonprofit group Public.Resource.Org, contended should be free, because federal documents are not covered by copyright.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The fees were "plowed back to the courts to finance technology, but the system [ran] a budget surplus of some $150 million, according to court reports," reported *The New York Times*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After reading Malamud's call for action, Swartz used a Perl computer script running on Amazon cloud servers to download the documents, using credentials belonging to a Sacramento library.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] From September 4 to 20, 2008, it accessed documents and uploaded them to a cloud computing service.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He released the documents to Malamud's organization.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On September 29, 2008, the GPO suspended the free trial, "pending an evaluation" of the program.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's actions were subsequently investigated by the FBI.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The case was closed after two months with no charges filed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] At a 2013 memorial for Swartz, Malamud recalled their work with PACER.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] District Court records out from behind PACER's "pay wall", he said, and found them full of privacy violations, including medical records and the names of minor children and confidential informants.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A more detailed account of his collaboration with Swartz on the PACER project appears in an essay on Malamud's website.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] *The New York Times* similarly reported Swartz had downloaded "an estimated 20 percent of the entire database".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Based on the facts that Swartz downloaded 2.7 million documents while PACER, at the time, contained 500 million, Lee concluded that Swartz downloaded less than one percent of the database.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2009, wanting to learn about effective activism, Swartz helped launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2010, Swartz co-founded Demand Progress, a political advocacy group that organizes people online to "take action by contacting Congress and other leaders, funding pressure tactics, and spreading the word" about civil liberties, government reform, and other issues.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] During academic year 2010–11, Swartz conducted research studies on political corruption as a Lab Fellow in Harvard University's Edmond J.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Now it's up to you to change the system. ...
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After the bill's defeat, Swartz was the keynote speaker at the F2C:Freedom to Connect 2012 event in Washington, D.C., on May 21, 2012.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He added, "We won this fight because everyone made themselves the hero of their own story.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz also spoke on the topic at an event organized by ThoughtWorks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz participated in Wikipedia beginning in August 2003 under the username AaronSw.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2006, he ran unsuccessfully for the Wikimedia Foundation's Board of Trustees.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz came to his conclusions by counting the number of characters editors added to particular articles, while Wales counted the total number of edits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In January 2013, shortly after he died, WikiLeaks said that Aaron Swartz had helped WikiLeaks and talked to Julian Assange in 2010 and 2011.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks also said they had "strong reasons to believe, but cannot prove" he may have been a source, possibly breaking WikiLeaks' rules about source anonymity.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks may have made the statements to imply that Swartz was targeted by the US Attorney's Office and Secret Service in order to get at WikiLeaks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] According to state and federal authorities, Swartz used JSTOR, a digital repository, to download a large number of academic journal articles through MIT's computer network over the course of a few weeks in late 2010 and early 2011.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Visitors to MIT's "open campus" were authorized to access JSTOR through its network; Swartz, as a research fellow at Harvard University, also had a JSTOR account.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On September 25, 2010, the IP address 18.55.6.215, part of the MIT network, began sending hundreds of PDF download requests per minute to the JSTOR website, enough to slow the site's performance.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] This prompted a block of the IP address.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In the morning, another IP address, also from within the MIT network, began sending more PDF download requests, resulting in a temporary block on the firewall level of all MIT computers in the entire 18.0.0.0/8 range.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] According to authorities, Swartz downloaded the documents through a laptop connected to a networking switch in a controlled-access wiring closet at MIT.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The closet's door was kept unlocked, according to press reports.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] When it was discovered, a video camera was placed in the room to record Swartz; his computer was left untouched.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The recording was stopped once Swartz was identified, but rather than pursue a civil lawsuit against him, JSTOR settled with him in June 2011; under the terms of the settlement, he surrendered the downloaded data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On July 30, 2013, JSTOR released 300 partially redacted documents used as incriminating evidence against Swartz, originally sent to the United States Attorney's Office in response to subpoenas in the case *United States v.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On the night of January 6, 2011, Swartz was arrested near the Harvard campus by MIT Police and a Secret Service agent, and arraigned in Cambridge District Court on two state charges of breaking and entering with intent to commit a felony.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On July 11, 2011, he was indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of wire fraud, computer fraud, unlawfully obtaining information from a protected computer, and recklessly damaging a protected computer.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On November 17, 2011, Swartz was indicted by a Middlesex County Superior Court grand jury on state charges of breaking and entering with intent, grand larceny, and unauthorized access to a computer network.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On December 16, 2011, state prosecutors filed a notice that they were dropping the two original charges, and the charges listed in the November 17, 2011, indictment were dropped on March 8, 2012.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] According to a spokesperson for the Middlesex County prosecutor, this was done to avoid impeding a federal prosecution headed by Stephen P.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Heymann, supported by evidence provided by Secret Service agent Michael S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On September 12, 2012, federal prosecutors filed a superseding indictment adding nine more felony counts, increasing Swartz's maximum criminal exposure to 50 years of imprisonment and $1 million in fines.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] During plea negotiations with Swartz's attorneys, the prosecutors offered to recommend a sentence of six months in a low-security prison if Swartz pled guilty to 13 federal crimes.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz and his lead attorney rejected the deal, opting instead for a trial where prosecutors would be forced to justify their pursuit of him.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The federal prosecution involved what was characterized by numerous critics (such as former Nixon White House counsel John Dean) as an "overcharging" 13-count indictment and "overzealous", "Nixonian" prosecution for alleged computer crimes, brought by then U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Attorney for Massachusetts Carmen Ortiz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz died by suicide on January 11, 2013.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After his death, federal prosecutors dropped the charges.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On December 4, 2013, due to a Freedom of Information Act suit by the investigations editor of *Wired* magazine, several documents related to the case were released by the Secret Service, including a video of Swartz entering the MIT network closet.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz was in an open relationship with Quinn Norton between 2007 and 2011 and dated Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman from 2011 until his death in 2013, contemplating marriage with her.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He also reportedly had same-sex relationships, and was skeptical of the idea of sexual identity.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Aside from his work, he posted frequently on Twitter, Reddit and his personal website.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On the evening of January 11, 2013, Swartz's girlfriend, Stinebrickner-Kauffman, found him dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A spokesperson for New York's Medical Examiner reported that he had hanged himself.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Days before Swartz's funeral, Lawrence Lessig eulogized him in an essay, "Prosecutor as Bully".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He decried the disproportionality of Swartz's prosecution and said, "The question this government needs to answer is why it was so necessary that Aaron Swartz be labeled a 'felon'.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] For in the 18 months of negotiations, that was what he was not willing to accept." Cory Doctorow wrote, "Aaron had an unbeatable combination of political insight, technical skill, and intelligence about people and issues.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] I think he could have revolutionized American (and worldwide) politics.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's funeral services were held on January 15, 2013, at Central Avenue Synagogue in Highland Park, Illinois.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, delivered a eulogy.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He is buried at Shalom Memorial Park in Arlington Heights.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* published a story based in part on an interview with Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] She told the *Journal* that Swartz lacked the money to pay for a trial and "it was too hard for him to ... make that part of his life go public" by asking for help.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He was also distressed, she said, because two of his friends had just been subpoenaed and because he no longer believed that MIT would try to stop the prosecution.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] For donations in his memory, Swartz's family recommended GiveWell, an organization Swartz admired, had collaborated with, and made his sole beneficiary in his will.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 19, hundreds attended a memorial at the Cooper Union, speakers at which included Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman, open source advocate Doc Searls, Creative Commons' Glenn Otis Brown, journalist Quinn Norton, Roy Singham of ThoughtWorks, and David Segal of Demand Progress.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 24, there was a memorial at the Internet Archive headquarters in San Francisco (video) at which Stinebrickner-Kauffman, Alex Stamos, Brewster Kahle, Peter Eckersley, and Carl Malamud spoke.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On February 4, a memorial was held in the Cannon House Office Building on Capitol Hill; speakers included Senator Ron Wyden and Representatives Darrell Issa, Alan Grayson, and Jared Polis.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Other lawmakers in attendance included Senator Elizabeth Warren and Representatives Zoe Lofgren and Jan Schakowsky.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Harvey Silverglate was a featured speaker at a Demand Progress rally in Swartz's memory.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A memorial also took place on March 12 at the MIT Media Lab.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On February 2, 2025, a statue of Swartz was unveiled at the Internet Archive building in San Francisco.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] This was organized by Pablo Peniche and Lisa Rein.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The statue stands in the building's lobby.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts, said in a statement: "As a parent and a sister, I can only imagine the pain felt by the family and friends of Aaron Swartz, ...
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 12, 2013, Swartz's family and partner issued a statement criticizing the prosecutors and MIT.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] At the time, MIT maintained an open-campus policy along with an "open network".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Two days after Swartz's death, MIT President L.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Rafael Reif commissioned professor Hal Abelson to lead an analysis of MIT's options and decisions relating to Swartz's "legal struggles".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] To help guide the fact-finding stage of the review, MIT created a website where community members could suggest questions and issues for the review to address.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's attorneys requested that all pretrial discovery documents be made public, a move MIT opposed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz allies have criticized MIT's opposition to releasing the evidence.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On July 26, 2013, the Abelson panel submitted a report to Reif, who authorized its public release on July 30.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The panel reported that MIT had not supported charges against Swartz and cleared the institution of wrongdoing, but also noted that despite MIT's advocacy for open access culture at the institutional level and beyond, the university never extended that support to Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The report revealed, for example, that while MIT considered issuing a public statement about its position on the case, it never did so.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] As editor Hrag Vartanian writes in *Hyperallergic*, the Brooklyn muralist BAMN ("By Any Means Necessary") created a mural of Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] "Swartz was an amazing human being who fought tirelessly for our right to a free and open Internet", BAMN said.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] "He was much more than just the 'Reddit guy'." On April 17, 2013, Yuval Noah Harari called Swartz "the first martyr of the Freedom of Information movement".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] But according to Harari, Swartz's stance did not illustrate belief in the freedom of persons or speech but stemmed from his generation's conviction that above all else, information should be free.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's legacy has reportedly strengthened the open access to scholarship movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In Illinois, his home state, Swartz's influence led state university faculties to adopt policies in favor of open access.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 13, 2013, members of Anonymous hacked two websites on the MIT domain, replacing them with tributes to Swartz that called on members of the Internet community to use his death as a rallying point for the open access movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The banner included a list of demands for improvements in the U.S. copyright system, along with Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto.* On the night of January 18, MIT's email system was taken offline for ten hours.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 22, email sent to MIT was redirected by hackers Aush0k and TibitXimer to the Korea Advanced Institute of Science & Technology.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] All other traffic to MIT was redirected to a computer at Harvard University that was publishing a statement headed "R.I.P Aaron Swartz", with text from a 2009 post by Swartz, accompanied by a chiptune version of "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] MIT regained full control after about seven hours.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In the early hours of January 26, Anonymous hacked the U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Sentencing Commission website, USSC.gov.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The homepage was replaced by an embedded YouTube video, *Anonymous Operation Last Resort*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The video statement said Swartz "faced an impossible choice".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A hacker downloaded "hundreds of thousands" of scientific-journal articles from a Swiss publisher's website and republished them on the open Web in Swartz's honor a week before the first anniversary of his death.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After Swartz's death, more than 50,000 people signed an online petition to the White House calling for Ortiz's removal "for overreach in the case of Aaron Swartz".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A similar petition was submitted calling for prosecutor Stephen Heymann's firing.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In January 2015, the White House declined both petitions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On August 3, 2013, Swartz was posthumously inducted into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] A hackathon was held in Swartz's memory around the date of his birthday in 2013.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On the weekend of November 8–10, 2013, inspired by Swartz's work and life, a second annual hackathon was held in at least 16 cities around the world.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Preliminary topics worked on at the 2013 Aaron Swartz Hackathon were privacy and software tools, transparency, activism, access, legal fixes, and a low-cost book scanner.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In January 2014, Lawrence Lessig led a walk across New Hampshire in honor of Swartz, rallying for campaign finance reform.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2017, the Turkish-Dutch artist Ahmet Öğüt commemorated Swartz in a work titled "Information Power to The People", which depicted his bust.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's supporters responded to news of his death with an effort called #PDFTribute to promote Open Access.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 12, Eva Vivalt, a development economist at the World Bank, began posting her academic articles online using the hashtag *#pdftribute* as a tribute to Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's story has exposed the topic of open access to scientific publications to wider audiences.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Many institutions and personalities have since campaigned for open access to scientific knowledge.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's death prompted calls for more open access to scholarly data (e.g., open science data).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The Think Computer Foundation and the Center for Information Technology Policy (CITP) at Princeton University announced scholarships awarded in memory of Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was posthumously awarded the American Library Association's James Madison Award for being an "outspoken advocate for public participation in government and unrestricted access to peer-reviewed scholarly articles".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In March, the editor and editorial board of the *Journal of Library Administration* resigned *en masse*, citing a dispute with the journal's publisher, Routledge.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] One board member wrote of a "crisis of conscience about publishing in a journal that was not open access" after Swartz died.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2002, Swartz had said that when he died, he wanted the contents of his hard drives made publicly available.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] House of Representatives—Republican Darrell Issa and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Jared Polis—all on the House Judiciary Committee, raised questions about the government's handling of the case.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Calling the charges against him "ridiculous and trumped up", Polis called Swartz a "martyr" whose death illustrated the need for Congress to limit the discretion of federal prosecutors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Senator Elizabeth Warren issued a statement saying that Swartz's "advocacy for Internet freedom, social justice, and Wall Street reform demonstrated ... the power of his ideas".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In a letter to Attorney General Eric Holder, Senator John Cornyn asked, "On what basis did the U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts conclude that her office's conduct was 'appropriate'?" and "Was the prosecution of Mr.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Issa, who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, announced that he would investigate the Justice Department's actions in prosecuting Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In a statement to *The Huffington Post*, he praised Swartz's work on "open government and free access to the people".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Issa's investigation garnered some bipartisan support.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 28, 2013, Issa and ranking committee member Elijah Cummings published a letter to Holder asking why federal prosecutors had filed the superseding indictment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On February 20, WBUR reported that Ortiz was expected to testify at an upcoming Oversight Committee hearing about her office's handling of Swartz's case.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On February 22, Associate Deputy Attorney General Steven Reich conducted a briefing for congressional staffers involved in the investigation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] They were told that Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* played a role in prosecutorial decision-making.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Congressional staffers left this briefing believing that prosecutors thought Swartz had to be convicted of a felony carrying at least a short prison sentence in order to justify having filed charges against him.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Excoriating the Department of Justice as the "Department of Vengeance", Stinebrickner-Kauffman told the *Guardian* that the DOJ had erred in relying on Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* as an indication of his beliefs by 2010.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] She said, "He was no longer a single issue activist.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He was into lots of things, from healthcare to climate change to money in politics." On March 6, Holder testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee that the case was "a good use of prosecutorial discretion".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In response, Stinebrickner-Kauffman issued a statement repeating and amplifying her claims of prosecutorial misconduct.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On March 22, Senator Al Franken wrote in a letter to Holder that "charging a young man like Mr.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Lofgren introduced a bill, *Aaron's Law* (H.R.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] 1196), to exclude terms of service violations from the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act and from the wire fraud statute.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Lessig wrote of the bill, "this is a critically important change....
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The CFAA was the hook for the government's bullying....
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In a single line: no longer would it be a felony to breach a contract." Professor Orin Kerr, a specialist in the nexus between computer law and criminal law, wrote that he had been arguing for precisely this sort of reform of the Act for years.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The ACLU also called for reform of the CFAA to "remove the dangerously broad criminalization of online activity".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The EFF mounted a campaign for these reforms.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Lessig's inaugural Chair lecture as Furman Professor of Law and Leadership was titled *Aaron's Laws: Law and Justice in a Digital Age*; he dedicated the lecture to Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The Aaron's Law bill stalled in committee.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Brian Knappenberger alleges this was due to Oracle Corporation's financial interest in maintaining the status quo.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act (FASTR) is a bill that would mandate earlier public release of taxpayer-funded research.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] FASTR has been described as "The Other Aaron's Law".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Senators Wyden and Cornyn introduced the Senate version in 2013, 2015 and 2017, while the bill was introduced to the House of Representatives by Lofgren, Mike Doyle, and Kevin Yoder.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Wyden wrote of the bill, "the FASTR act provides that access to taxpayer funded research should never be hidden behind a paywall." The legislation did not pass, but it prompted more open access on the part of the US government.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Since 2013, Aaron Swartz Day has been celebrated on his birthday, November 8, with hackathons and livestreamed talks related to the many issues Swartz was passionate about, such as open access and progressive politics and economics.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Past speakers include Chelsea Manning, Barrett Brown, Trevor Timm of the Freedom of the Press Foundation, Cory Doctorow, Cindy Cohn, Jason Leopold, and Brewster Kahle.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz has been featured in various works of art and has posthumously received dedications from numerous artists.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He appeared in a few documentaries, including *Aardvark'd: 12 Weeks with Geeks* in 2005.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] After leaving Reddit he appeared in *Steal This Film II* (2007).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Swartz's first posthumous work was in 2013, when Kenneth Goldsmith dedicated his "Printing out the Internet" exhibition to Swartz.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] On January 11, 2014, marking the first anniversary of his death, a preview was released of *The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz*, a documentary about Swartz, the NSA and SOPA.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The film was officially released at the January 2014 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] *Democracy Now!* covered the release of the documentary, as well as Swartz's life and legal case, in a sprawling interview with director Brian Knappenberger, Swartz's father, brother, and his attorney.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The documentary is released under a Creative Commons License; it debuted in theaters and on-demand in June 2014.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Mashable called the documentary "a powerful homage to Aaron Swartz".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Its debut at Sundance received a standing ovation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In October 2014, *Killswitch*, a documentary film featuring Swartz, Lessig, Tim Wu, and Edward Snowden, premiered at the Woodstock Film Festival, where it won the award for Best Editing.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The film focuses on Swartz's role in advocating for internet freedoms.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] In February 2015, Congressman Alan Grayson invited *Killswitch* to screen at the Capitol Visitor Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The event was held on the eve of the Federal Communications Commission's historic decision on net neutrality.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] At the event, Grayson, Lessig, and Free Press CEO Craig Aaron spoke about Swartz and his fight for a free and open Internet.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Grayson called *Killswitch* "one of the most honest accounts of the battle to control the Internet—and access to information itself." Richard von Busack of the Metro Silicon Valley said *Killswitch* contains "some of the most lapidary use of found footage this side of The Atomic Café".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Fred Swegles of the *Orange County Register* wrote, "Anyone who values unfettered access to online information is apt to be captivated by *Killswitch*, a gripping and fast-paced documentary." Kathy Gill of GeekWire wrote, "*Killswitch* is much more than a dry recitation of technical history.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Director Ali Akbarzadeh, producer Jeff Horn, and writer Chris Dollar created a human-centered story.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] He appeared in the unreleased film *War for the Web* where he had been interviewed a year prior to his death.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] The documentary was ultimately cancelled as it failed to reach its funding goal, but the footage was later used in *The Internet's Own Boy*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/aaron-swartz] Another biographical film about Swartz, *Think Aaron*, was being developed by HBO Films as of 2020.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] Houdebine used the GFP gene found in the jellyfish, *Aequorea victoria*, that fluoresces green when exposed to blue light.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] This is a protein used in many standard biological experiments involving fluorescence.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] When Alba was exposed to such light, she would literally glow green — though photos by Kac showing the entire organism, including its hair, glowing a uniform green have had their veracity challenged.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] Kac described Alba as an animal that did not exist in nature.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] In an article published in *The Boston Globe*, Houdebine said his group had already been using rabbits in its research, but that he was intrigued by Kac's desire to involve the public, and had ''never considered'' whether an entire animal would glow in the dark.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] This article generated a global media scandal, which caused Houdebine to distance himself from Kac's work.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] All subsequent media articles present variations on Houdebine's disengagement effort.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] Houdebine himself said he agreed to participate in a debate, but the research facility where they had made the rabbits had not given consent.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] Kac continued to spread the images of 'his' Alba and became widely recognised as BioArtist, whereas Houdebine regretted being vague.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] In 2002, a US reporter called INRA (France), where Houdebine works, and was told that Alba had died.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] The reporter published an article stating that Alba was dead but the only evidence she provided was to quote Houdebine as saying: "I was informed one day that bunny was dead without any reason.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alba-rabbit] In the 2007 European Molecular Biology Organization Members Meeting in Barcelona, Louis-Marie Houdebine presented in detail his version of the reality of 'the GFP rabbit story', placing emphasis on sensationalism by journalists and the TV media.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has been described as "Science's Pirate Queen".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2016, *Nature* included her in their list of the top ten "people who mattered" in science.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Since 2011, she has been living in Russia.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was born in Almaty, Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic, on 6 November 1988.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She identifies as multiracial, with Armenian, Slavic and Asian roots.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra was raised by a single mother, who was an accomplished computer programmer.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra started programming at the age of 12, making web pages in HTML and later writing in PHP, Delphi, and assembly languages.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She attempted to create a Tamagotchi powered by artificial intelligence.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She performed her first computer hack at the age of 14; using SQL injection, she obtained access to all logins and passwords of her home internet provider.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Later, she discovered there were more vulnerabilities of the cross-site scripting type.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She reported these issues to the internet provider, hoping to get a job with them, but this did not happen.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Instead, the provider cut off her internet access.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra wrote in her blog that she first hacked a publisher's website when she was 16.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] The publisher was MIT Press, which published online books on neuroscience, but they were locked behind a paywall that she could not afford.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra wrote a PHP program that exploited a vulnerability on the website to download paywalled books without payment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2009, she obtained a Bachelor of Science degree in computer science from the Satbayev University, specializing in information security.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She studied the possibility of using brainwaves measured using electroencephalography (EEG) for authentication instead of using a password.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] While working on her thesis, Elbakyan discovered the paywall problem with accessing journal articles, as her university did not have access to many publications related to her work.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra became interested in developing brain–computer interfaces and in 2010 she joined the University of Freiburg to work on such a project, which eventually led to her summer internship in neuroscience at Georgia Institute of Technology in the United States.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] The same year, Elbakyan spoke at the Humanity+ Summit at Harvard on the topic "Brain-Computer Interfacing, Consciousness, and the Global Brain".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan's idea was to develop a new kind of brain-machine interface that would merge human and machine qualia.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She also participated in the *Towards a Science of Consciousness* conference that was held in Tucson, Arizona with the poster "Consciousness in Mixed Systems: Merging Artificial and Biological Minds via Brain-Machine Interface".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] From 2012 to 2014, she was a master's student at Higher School of Economics in Moscow, but then dropped out.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] According to a 2016 interview, her neuroscience research was on hold, but she was enrolled in a history of science master's program at a private university in an undisclosed location.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Her thesis would focus on scientific communication.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Later, she has focused more on religious topics, and in 2019, she graduated from Saint Petersburg State University with a master's degree in linguistics on the topic of biblical languages.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan developed Sci-Hub in 2011, when she lived in Kazakhstan.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] When academic publisher Elsevier sued Sci-Hub in the US in 2015, Elbakyan wrote a letter to the judge, wherein she explained her motives for starting the project: she could not afford to pay for each of the hundreds of papers she needed for her research project, so she had to pirate them.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She founded her website to help others in the same situation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In the letter Elbakyan has provided various arguments in support for her cause, such as Elsevier not being an author of papers, and not paying the authors, mentioning that "The general opinion in research community is that research papers should be distributed for free (open access), not sold".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elsevier was granted an injunction against her and $15 million in damages.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Following a lawsuit, Elbakyan remained in hiding due to the risk of extradition.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] There were also lawsuits against Sci-Hub and Elbakyan from other publishers and in other countries.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] On 17 February 2023, a court in India refused to dismiss a blocking application submitted by the legal representatives of the publishers; nonetheless, the legal representatives of Elbakyan are working on a new creative legal strategy, namely the mandatory economic angle.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan is a strong supporter of the open access movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her, Sci-Hub is a true implementation of open access principle in science.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She believes that science should be open to all and not behind paywalls.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She has described herself as a devout pirate and thinks that copyright law prevents the free exchange of information online and the free distribution of knowledge on the Internet.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2018, she asked supporters of Sci-Hub to join their local Pirate Party in order to fight for copyright laws to be changed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has stated that she is inspired by communist ideals, and considers the common ownership of ideas to be essential for scientific progress.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In her 2016 interview to *Vox*, she said: "I like the idea of communism, and the idea that knowledge should be common and not intellectual property is very relevant.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] That is especially true for information.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Research articles are used for communication in science.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] But the word 'communication' implies common ownership by itself." She referenced the work of Robert Merton, who considered communism to be a part of scientific ethos.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her, Sci-Hub is fighting for communism in science and against the current state of things when knowledge has become the private property of corporations, because knowledge belongs to everyone.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan does not strictly label herself a Marxist, but adopts much of its propositions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She wanted to join either the Communist Party of the Russian Federation or Pirate Party of Russia, but was unable to as membership in political parties is restricted to those with Russian citizenship.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] A few months before the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022, when asked in an interview if she was still loyal to Putin, she responded that she is neither aligned with Putin nor with the Russian liberal opposition, reiterating that she identifies herself first and foremost as a communist.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was in conflict with the liberal, pro-Western wing of the Russian scientific community.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her interview, she was attacked on the Internet by 'science popularizers' who supported liberal views that led to the shutdown of Sci-Hub in Russia in 2017 for a few days.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In particular, Elbakyan was strongly critical of the former Dynasty Foundation (shut down in 2015) and its associated figures.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She believes that the foundation was politicized, tied to Russia's liberal opposition, and fit the legal definition of a "foreign agent".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Dynasty's founder, in her opinion, financed researchers whose political views agreed with its own.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan states that after she began to investigate the foundation's activities and published her findings online, she became the target of a cyberharassment campaign by Dynasty's supporters.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In December 2019, *The Washington Post* reported that Elbakyan was under investigation by the US Justice Department for suspected ties to Russia's military intelligence arm — the GRU — to steal U.S. military secrets from defense contractors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has denied this, saying that Sci-Hub "...is not in any way directly affiliated with Russian or some other country's intelligence," but noting that "...of course, there could be some indirect help.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] The same as with donations, anyone can send them; they are completely anonymous, so I do not know who exactly is donating to Sci-Hub.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] There could be some help that I'm simply unaware of.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] On May 8, 2021, Elbakyan tweeted that the FBI had served a subpoena to Apple seeking her iCloud data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] The tweet included a screengrab of the notice from Apple.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] In December 2016, *Nature* named Elbakyan as one of the 10 people who most mattered in science that year.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Some researchers who use Sci-Hub thank Elbakyan in the acknowledgments section of their papers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] For her actions in creating Sci-Hub, Elbakyan has been called a hero, for example by Nobel laureate Randy Schekman.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] *Ars Technica* has compared her to Aaron Swartz, and *The New York Times* has compared her to Edward Snowden.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Edward Snowden acknowledged Sci-Hub to be one of the most important websites for academics in the world.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] She has also been called a modern-day "Robin Hood", a "Robin Hood of science", and "Science's Pirate Queen".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was nominated twice for John Maddox Prize and made it to the final shortlist.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/alexandra-elbakyan] Some researchers say that Elbakyan deserves a Nobel Prize for her work.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Amateur chemistry shares its early history with that of chemistry in general.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Pioneers of modern chemistry such as Robert Boyle and Antoine Lavoisier were gentlemen scientists who pursued their research independently from their source of income.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Only with the coming of the Industrial Revolution, and the rise of universities as research institutions, did any significant distinction between amateurs and professionals emerge.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Nevertheless, amateur progress lasted well into the 19th century.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] For example, in 1886, Charles Martin Hall co-invented the Hall-Héroult process for extracting aluminium from its oxide whilst working in a woodshed behind his family home.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The history of amateur chemistry ties in well with that of chemistry in general.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The history of chemistry represents a time span from ancient history to the present.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] By 1000 BC, civilizations used technologies that would eventually form the basis to the various branches of chemistry.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] These processes include extracting metals from ores, making pottery and glazes, fermenting beer and wine, extracting chemicals from plants for medicine and perfume, rendering fat into soap, making glass, and making alloys like bronze.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Throughout much of the 20th century, amateur chemistry was an unexceptional hobby, with high-quality chemistry sets readily available, and laboratory suppliers freely selling to hobbyists.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] For example, Linus Pauling had no difficulty in procuring potassium cyanide at the age of eleven.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Many academics, from researchers to university professors, and even Nobel prize laureates, have acknowledged that at least part of their interest in sciences could be traced back to chemistry sets and home labs when they were young.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] These include Dorothy Hodgkin, Robert F.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Phillips, Steven Weinberg, Peter Licence, etc.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] However, due to increasing concerns about terrorism, drugs, and safety, suppliers became increasingly reluctant to sell to amateurs, and chemistry sets were steadily toned down.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] This trend has gradually continued, leaving hobbyists in many parts of the world without access to most reagents.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Even as recently as 2023, amateur chemists on forums and YouTube channels have been credited by academic researchers for suggesting and discussing novel viable synthetic routes before full investigations by the latter.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Home-based chemistry labs were explored as a way to remotely teach students during the COVID-19 pandemic, especially since many local and state-level governments across the world imposed lockdowns or other types of restrictions to contain the spread of the virus.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Whilst the hobby is probably legal in most jurisdictions,[b] the relationship between amateur chemists and law enforcement agencies is often fraught.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Hobbyists are often affected by laws intended to fight drugs and terrorism.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Furthermore, many chemical supply houses refuse to sell to amateurs, with such policies sometimes being stated openly.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Medium-sized suppliers and multinationals have whole departments, sometimes named Compliance or Regulatory affairs, tasked with periodically checking and implementing new regulations regarding chemicals on their companies.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In Canada, a wide range of basic laboratory reagents such as nitric acid and hydrogen peroxide are restricted as "explosives precursors".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Two of the main legal texts in Canada restricting the sale of certain chemicals are the Explosives Act, and the Explosives Regulations, 2013 (SOR/2013-211).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In late 2008, Lewis Casey, an 18-year-old college student from Saskatchewan, was arrested for owning a small chemistry lab in his family's garage.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] After the raid, the police initially claimed that it was a meth lab, but withdrew the drug charge a few days later.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The Crown withdrew criminal charges against him on Oct.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Those regulations may contain provisions affecting one or more types of "agents" (e.g. manufacturers, resellers, distributors, etc.), end users, or both.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Reagent manufacturers typically require customers to sign an end user declaration before accepting and processing the sale of a chemical listed on these schedules.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] One of the cornerstones of EU legislation on hazardous chemicals is the Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals (REACH), which is defined in Regulation (EC) No.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On the topic of explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) No.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] 98/2013 introduced rules to harmonize the sale, possession and use of several substances across all EU countries.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] It requires that each member state must define a National Contact Point to which economic operators must report suspicious transactions, thefts, and disappearances of significant quantities involving scheduled substances.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On 1 February 2021, Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 amended REACH and repealed Regulation (EC) No.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The newer one is designed to ban the sale and possession of explosives precursors by members of the general public above given concentrations.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Any individual can own these chemicals provided their concentration is below or equal to a given limit (e.g. for sulfuric acid up to 15% conc. in weight).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Said upper limit allowed can be increased (e.g. for sulfuric acid, up to 40% conc.) by requesting a license to the national authority.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Professional users are not affected by these thresholds.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] However, professional users and members of the general public must also report significant disappearances and thefts of restricted explosives precursors within 24 hours of detection to the national contact point.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Regarding waste management, it might be considered acceptable to dispose of some acidic or basic solutions by neutralizing and flushing them down the drain, provided that they don't contain other hazardous substances and the reaction products aren't hazardous either.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] However, other types of wastes must be disposed by handling them to an authorised waste management entity in an appropriate container, usually HDPE jerry cans.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Such entities require each container received to be appropriately labeled with several details, which may include GHS hazard pictograms, the EWC (European Waste Catalogue) code, also called LoW (List of Waste) code, that identifies the type of waste.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] These codes were defined by the Commission Decision 2000/532/EC, later amended by Commission Decision 2014/955/EU.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Several chemicals, especially solvents, are subject to taxes for certain uses.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] One such example is ethanol, due to its potential use in alcoholic drinks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Both Council Directive 92/81/EEC, and Council Directive 2003/96/EC, which repealed the former, impose taxes on several hydrocarbons that can be used as fuels.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Regulations regarding hazardous chemicals in this country include the Explosives Act (Sprengstoffgesetz), and the Hazardous Substances Ordinance (Gefahrstoffverordnung, abbreviated as GefStoffV), which is part of the Chemicals Act (Chemikaliengesetz, abbreviated as ChemG).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Another one is the Chemicals Prohibition Ordinance (Chemikalien-Verbotsverordnung, abbreviated as ChemVerbotsV).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 was transposed into German law in the Precursor Act (Ausgangsstoffgesetz, Precursor Act, abbreviated as AusgStG).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] German amateur chemists have been raided by the police, despite not being in the possession of illegal chemicals.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Regarding explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) 98/2013, was transposed in the Statutory Instrument No 611/2014.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In Italy, regulations regarding explosives precursors have been approved as the Ministry of the Interior's Circolare 557/PAS/U/004997/XV.H.MASS(53)5, titled Identificazione e tracciabilità degli esplosivi per uso civile: - Indicazioni operative e gestione delle scorte.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 was implemented through the Legge 23 dicembre 2021, n.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] 238, whose article 13 modifies the Decreto Legislativo 14 settembre 2009, n.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] 133, adding a whole chapter to the latter (Chapter II, after article 17).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On the topic of explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) 98/2013, was transposed into the Portuguese legal system as the Decree Law 56/2016, of 29th of August.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] This Decree Law was, in turn, repealed by Decree Law 62/2021, of 26th of July, which transposes Regulation (EU) 2019/1148.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On January 3, 1994, Eduardo Rey Díaz, a 13-year-old boy from Getxo, Basque Country, was at a friend's house doing an experiment using materials from a chemistry set.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] After approaching the open end of a graduated cylinder containing a flammable substance to an open flame, a deflagration occurred, which left him with severe burns in his hands and face.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The manufacturer was sued and later fined.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Less than a year and a half later, in December 22, 1995, an 11-year-old boy and his 8-year-old sister from Galicia, suffered third and second-degree burns in 70 and 60% of their bodies.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] After watching them while they performed an experiment using another set from the same company, their mother ordered them to put the game away and left the room, but they kept playing.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] As a result of incorrectly handling the set, a deflagration occurred, and the company was sued and charged again.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] By the 2010s, many of them were no longer available.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Despite these incidents, the positive impact of chemistry sets on kickstarting the curiosity of children, some of whom would later become professional scientists and engineers, has been acknowledged.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] According to the Resolution of 20 November 2013 of the Spanish State Secretariat for Security, the National Contact Point for this country is the Intelligence Center for Counter-Terrorism and Organized Crime (CITCO).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Before the transposition of Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 into Spanish Law 25/2022, of 1st of November, explosives precursors were addressed by Law 8/2017, of 8 November, on explosives precursors, which the former repealed and replaced.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On the other hand, drug precursors are addressed by the Law 4/2009, of 15 June, on drug precursors control, and the Royal Decree 129/2017, of 24 February, by which the Drug Precursors Control Regulation is approved.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The first ones (purchases and sales) must include information on the quantities, full contact details and address, and NIF or DNI number of the suppliers or buyers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, the storage of chemicals, including reagents, flammable solvents, and gas cylinders, is regulated by Royal Decree 656/2017, of 23 June.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Industrial establishments also need to take into account Royal Decree 2267/2004, of 3 December, by which the fire safety regulations for industrial establishments are approved.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In general, the topic of *hazardous waste management* is discussed on Law 22/2011, of 28 July, on wastes and contaminated soils, which was repealed and replaced by Law 7/2022, of 8 April.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The transport of wastes is regulated as well, by the Royal Decree 553/2020, of 2 June.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Business that meet the definition of 'waste producers' or 'waste management facilities' need to obtain an Environmental Identification Number (Número de identificación medioambiental, NIMA).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Said numbers are issued by the government of the autonomous community where the business is located.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Several EU regulations regarding special taxes have been transposed to Spanish regulations in Law 38/1992, of 28 December, of Special Taxes.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] It was later extended by the Royal Decree 1165/1995, of 7 July, by which the Regulation on Special Taxes is approved.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] According to article 79 of the latter, even though ethanol is subject to a special tax due to its potential use in spirits, its use in scientific research can be exempted.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] This exemption requires obtaining an Activity and Establishment Code (Código de Actividad y del Establecimiento, CAE), which allows to request a refund from the Tax Agency (Agencia Tributaria) by submitting a filled form model 572.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Said code is composed of 13 characters, the first two being "ES", then three zeros, two characters identifying the local management office, two more characters for the activity, a sequential inscription number made up of three characters, and finally a control letter.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] A refund can also be requested for the special tax on hydrocarbons as long as they aren't used as fuels, according to article 109 the same Royal Decree (1165/1995, of 7 July).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] One of the laws regulating chemicals in Sweden is the Act on flammable and explosive goods (Lag om brandfarliga och explosiva varor).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In September 2018, a 29-year-old physician and amateur chemist and his girlfriend were arrested at their home on in Nord-Jæren, two days after inquiring a local pharmacy about the availability of 35% hydrogen peroxide.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] He explained that he had an accident while camping, suffering a wound that he stitched himself.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Being a physician and seeing the effect of flame-sterilizing on his surgical instruments, he was looking for a milder alternative that could also be used to disinfect wounds.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] However, his enquiry triggered the submission of an alert to KRIPOS, which sent a few police officers to the house.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] These officers would, in turn, find the chemicals from his lab, and arrest him.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] One law in this country that regulates flammable chemicals, gas cylinders, and explosive substances is the Fire and Explosion Protection Act (Brann- og eksplosjonsvernloven).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In the UK it is a criminal offence for members of the general public to purchase, and for business to sell, certain types of poisons or explosives precursors to those of the former group without a valid EPP license.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Purchasing substances on this list is restricted since 26 May 2015, and its possession is also restricted since 3 March 2016.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Since July 1st 2018, the acquisition of sulphuric acid in concentrations above 15% in weight by members of the general public also requires an EPP licence, which has impacted lead-acid battery sellers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On 26 February 2022, three men, aged between 20 and 25, were arrested in Wigan on suspicions they had violated Section 4 of the Explosives Act.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] A search warrant had found several chemicals on their flat.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Soon after, the eldest was released on bail, and the other two were also released under investigation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Two years later, in May 2024, the investigation concluded that they had just been doing amateur chemistry, and none of the three were charged.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Some regulations regarding restricted chemicals in this country include the Poison Act 1972, which was amended by the Deregulation Act 2015, and the Control of Poisons and Explosives Precursors Regulations 2015.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On 1 October 2023, a new set of amendments to the Poisons Act 1972, known as the "Control of Poisons and Explosives Precursors Regulations 2023", came into force.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The sulfides of aluminium, calcium, magnesium, sodium and zinc, as well as arsenic and its compounds are now considered "regulated poisons" rather than just "reportable poisons".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Finally, sulfur, all metal phosphides, all metal sulfides, all metal polysulfides and sodium hypochlorite solutions above 6% available chlorine have been added to the "reportable poisons" list.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Directly related to the above is the Offensive Weapons Act 2019, which forbids the sale of corrosive chemicals to minors, as well as their shipment to residential addresses or lockers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] In the United States, the Drug Enforcement Administration maintains lists regarding the classification of illicit drugs, which contain chemicals that are used to manufacture the controlled substances/illicit drugs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The lists are designated within The Controlled Substances Act, 21 U.S.C. § 802, paragraphs 34 (list I) and 35 (list II).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, some regions have stringent regulations concerning the ownership of chemicals and equipment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] For example, Texas once required the registration of even the most basic laboratory glassware.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] However, this requirement was repealed on June 6, 2019.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Several states define hazardous waste management laws, one example being the California Hazardous Waste Control Law (Cal.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Passed in 2017, California Assembly Bill (AB) 245 raised the maximum administrative and civil penalties for violations of said law from $25,000 per day of noncompliance to $70,000 per day.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] United Nuclear, an amateur science supplier based in New Mexico was raided in June 2003 at the behest of the U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Consumer Product Safety Commission, and subsequently fined $7,500 for "Selling Illegal Fireworks Components".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Almost a year later, Jack Robison, then a 19-year-old chemistry student at the Holyoke Community College, received a visit from members of the Massachusetts State Police, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives, and the FBI.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] They asked him questions regarding several videos on small-scale experiments he had posted two years earlier on YouTube involving energetic materials, including PETN, potassium nitrate, and RDX, and wanted to check his mother's house basement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] He was initially charged with three counts of malicious explosion and one count of possessing explosives with the intent to harm people or property, facing up to 60 years in prison, but was found not guilty after trial.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Amateur chemistry has been depicted multiple times in mass media, through different formats.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] The protagonists or other characters of animated television series like Dexter's Laboratory, Tracey McBean and The Simpsons (e.g. on the Haw-Haw Land episode) are sometimes displayed performing chemistry experiments in their own laboratories.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] On the other hand, there are several YouTube channels focused in chemical experiments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/amateur-chemistry] Most of them are run by amateurs, mostly by professional communicators and organizations, though there are a small sample of professional chemists.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive emerged from the **Pirate Library Mirror** (**PiLiMi**) project, an anonymous effort to mirror shadow libraries that completed a full copy of Z-Library in September 2022.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] PiLiMi acknowledged that it "deliberately violated the copyright law in most countries".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The project's initial focus was on preservation rather than on making its data searchable.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Days after US law enforcement seized several Z-Library domains and arrested its alleged operators in November 2022, PiLiMi member Anna (also known as Anna Archivist) launched Anna's Archive, which initially displayed results from Z-Library and LibGen.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has been variously described as a search engine, a metasearch engine, and a shadow library itself.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It operates several mirror sites under different top-level domains.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Its source code is dedicated to the public domain under the CC0 license.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site does not itself host any files (which it claims makes it nonliable for downloads of copyrighted works), but it indexes metadata and links to "third-party" downloads.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It also offers downloads through the IPFS protocol.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site's "source libraries" include LibGen, Sci-Hub, Z-Library, the Internet Archive, DuXiu, MagzDB, Nexus/STC, and HathiTrust; Open Library, WorldCat, and Google Books are listed as metadata-only sources.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Some of these datasets are already publicly accessible, while others are scraped or otherwise privately acquired for distribution.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] They are then released in bulk with torrent files so as to make them resilient to website takedowns.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] As of May 2026, Anna's Archive includes 64,416,225 books and 95,689,473 papers, and its unified list of torrents totals roughly 1.1 petabytes in size.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In March 2025, it averaged over 650,000 daily downloads, roughly 10 times the estimated distribution of the New York Public Library.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive uses a multi-layered server architecture designed for resilience against takedowns and outages.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] According to a 2023 blog post by the site's operators, the backend runs on Flask, MariaDB, and Elasticsearch, hosted on inexpensive servers that are proxied through separate providers to shield the actual hosting infrastructure from legal requests.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Multiple redundant proxy servers and application servers are maintained so that if any single provider terminates service, the site can continue to operate.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site initially used Cloudflare's free tier as an additional caching and DDoS protection layer, taking advantage of Cloudflare's legal position that it acts as a utility rather than a hosting provider and is therefore not directly subject to DMCA takedown requests.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] However, following court orders associated with the Spotify lawsuit in January 2026, Cloudflare disabled its nameservers for several Anna's Archive domains.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] At least some of the site's domains subsequently shifted to DDoS-Guard, a Russian DDoS-protection and content delivery provider.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has registered domains through a variety of registrars across multiple jurisdictions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Several of its domains, including its `.li` and `.gl` domains, have been registered through Njalla, a privacy-focused domain registration service operated by Njalla SRL in Costa Rica, which registers domains in its own name on behalf of customers to shield their identities.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site's data is standardized under the Anna's Archive Containers (AAC) format, introduced in August 2023 to allow for incremental releases.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Each container consists of metadata and optionally associated binary data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Metadata files use line-delimited JSON compressed with Zstandard, while binary data files are stored alongside them in structured directories.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The format is designed to be machine-readable, easy to distribute via torrents, and compatible with the site's existing stack of MariaDB, Elasticsearch, and Python.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive describes itself as a nonprofit, claiming that membership fees and donations are mostly spent on server infrastructure and that none are personally used by the site's operators.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It awards memberships and monetary "bounties" to some volunteer contributors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site operates a tiered download system.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] High-speed downloads on Anna's Archive are only available to users with a paid membership, with the number of fast downloads permitted per 24-hour period varying by membership tier; multiple memberships can be combined additively.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Non-members must use slower options with browser verification to prevent abuse by bots.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] A waitlist-based system allows free users to access somewhat faster servers by limiting the number of concurrent downloads.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive offers high-speed access to its full collection via SFTP to groups training large language models (LLMs) in exchange for large contributions of money or data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It said it provided such access to about 30 companies (primarily based in China) as of January 2025, including both LLM companies and data brokers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] DeepSeek's VL model was partly trained on ebook data from the site.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Some lawyers have criticized claims that this constitutes fair use under US copyright law, citing precedent for the importance of market harm.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Because of its legal status, the site states that it cannot accept payments through conventional banking channels directly.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Instead, it relies on cryptocurrency as well as alternative methods such as Amazon gift cards, Cash App and Alipay.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The operators have stated that the need to remain anonymous necessitates avoiding traditional payment processors, and that only a small number of companies support virtual debit cards paid for with cryptocurrency.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has said its objectives are to "catalog all the books in existence" and "track humanity's progress toward making all these books easily available in digital form".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It has been described as both continuing and greatly extending the ambitions of earlier shadow libraries with its vision of a "universal library" that preserves as many books as possible.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It has been interpreted as part of an ascendant "culture of mistrust towards corporations, institutions, governments, and laws... that perhaps began with the financial collapse of 2008 and the Occupy Wall Street movements" which saw the rise of decentralizing technologies.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna has justified their opposition to copyright on ethical grounds, stating that they "believe that preserving and hosting these files is morally right" and that they and other shadow librarians believe that "information wants to be free".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] They have suggested that copyright law must be reformed as a matter of national security, proposing that Western countries make legal carveouts for text and data mining so as to remain ahead in the AI arms race.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna cites programmer and information activist Aaron Swartz as inspiring the project's collection of metadata.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The site recommends Swartz's writings as well as Stephen Witt's *How Music Got Free* and Michele Boldrin and David K.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Levine's *Against Intellectual Monopoly*, which criticize existing copyright law and have been associated with the copyleft movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Since 2023, Anna's Archive domains have appeared in the annual Notorious Markets List of the Office of the United States Trade Representative, which highlights digital and physical markets allegedly involved in large-scale intellectual property infringement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] These reports describe the site as related to Sci-Hub and LibGen.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In response to a request for comment by the Office on its 2023 List, the Association of American Publishers identified Anna's Archive as an infringing site, and analyzed its cryptocurrency wallets to find that it had received over $29,000 in funds as of July 2023.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In October 2023, Anna's Archive was reported to have scraped the entirety of WorldCat, the world's largest bibliographic database, and made its proprietary data freely available, which Anna described as "a major milestone in mapping out all the books in the world".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] OCLC, WorldCat's maintainer, responded by suing the site in an Ohio federal court in January 2024, claiming the scrape was achieved through cyberattacks on its servers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It sought over $5 million in total damages and an injunction to stop Anna's Archive from scraping or sharing its data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] OCLC clarified that although its internal systems were not breached, it believes the site's actions legally constitute hacking.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The only named defendant denied any involvement with the scrape or Anna's Archive.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Technology writer Glyn Moody criticized the suit as "costly and pointless", saying it went against OCLC's stated mission of making information accessible.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In July 2024, in the wake of the suit, the `.org` mirror of Anna's Archive was replaced with a new `.gs` mirror to avoid falling under US jurisdiction; however, soon afterward, the `.gs` domain was suspended and the mirror reverted to the original `.org` domain.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In March 2025, the court deferred judgement on aspects of the case to the Supreme Court of Ohio over concerns about its legal novelty, denying both a motion for default judgement from OCLC and a motion to dismiss from the named defendant.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In April, OCLC reached an agreement with the named defendant to drop her from the case, focusing instead on obtaining judgement against the site itself.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In November, OCLC dropped the demand for damages, focusing its efforts on obtaining an injunction that would compel third-party intermediaries to stop the sharing of the data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, federal district judge Michael H.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Watson issued a default judgement in favor of OCLC, requiring Anna's Archive to delete the WorldCat data and preventing it from scraping or sharing WorldCat in the future.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive was not expected to comply with the ruling; OCLC stated that it "hopes to take the judgment to website hosting services".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The plaintiffs in the case, a group of authors including Richard Kadrey, Sarah Silverman, and Christopher Golden, alleged that CEO Mark Zuckerberg personally authorized the use of shadow libraries.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The company had argued that its use of copyrighted data in AI training constituted fair use.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In June 2025, the court partially ruled in favor of Meta, finding that the training was "highly transformative" and therefore fair use.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Vince Chhabria, the judge in the case, emphasized that the ruling did not mean that Meta's actions were in fact legitimate, but said that the plaintiffs failed to develop strong arguments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] He identified "market dilution" as a convincing argument for financial harm not pursued by the plaintiffs — the idea that "by training generative AI models with copyrighted works, companies are creating something that often will dramatically undermine the market for those works".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In December 2025, Anna's Archive reportedly scraped almost 300 terabytes of data from music streaming service Spotify, publishing 256 million rows of track metadata and stating plans to publish 86 million audio files.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] While the audio accounted for only 37% of Spotify's full collection, it represented 99.6% of listens on the platform.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In response, the company stated that it had "identified and disabled the nefarious user accounts that engaged in unlawful scraping".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Some criticized the release's lack of coverage for less streamed songs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The metadata release was compared to the open database MusicBrainz, which contains roughly 5 million tracks, around 37 times smaller.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Pro-copyright campaigners predicted that the leaked music would be used to train AI models.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The same month, Spotify, alongside major record labels including Universal Music Group, Sony Music, and Warner Music, filed a lawsuit against the unknown operators of Anna's Archive in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The complaint alleged mass copyright infringement, breach of contract, DMCA violations, and violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, accusing the site of circumventing Spotify's digital rights management systems.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The lawsuit was initially filed under seal "so that Anna's Archive cannot pre-emptively frustrate" countermeasures they seek.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, the court granted a temporary restraining order, followed by a preliminary injunction issued on January 16 by US District Court Judge Jed Rakoff.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The injunction ordered Anna's Archive to cease hosting, linking to, or distributing the copyrighted works, and also targeted third-party intermediaries including domain registries, hosting companies, and Cloudflare.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] As a result, several Anna's Archive domain names were suspended, including the `.org` domain overseen by the Public Interest Registry and the `.se` domain.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive initially believed that the suspension was unrelated to their activities.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In response to a March 2024 lawsuit accusing Nvidia of training LLMs on data from a shadow library the company disputed the characterization of Anna's Archive and other repositories as "shadow libraries", despite Anna's own use of the term.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, additional evidence was presented in the case suggesting that Nvidia also directly contacted Anna's Archive in order to gain high-speed access to its data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive denied ever dealing with Nvidia directly, and raised the possibility that Nvidia used an intermediary party to avoid legal issues.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] On January 29, 2026, Nvidia filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Following a lawsuit brought in March 2026 by a group of 13 publishers, on 19 May 2026, U.S.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] District Court for the Southern District of New York issued a default judgment ordering the website to immediately cease copying and distributing millions of files that it had illegally downloaded.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The publishers were awarded a $19.5 million default judgment, and the judge ordered a global domain takedown.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In January 2024, Italy's national communications agency ordered major internet service providers (ISPs) in the country to block Anna's Archive due to a copyright complaint by the Italian Publishers Association.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] An investigation by the Digital Services Directorate confirmed the presence of copyrighted works on the site and found that some of its servers were likely owned by a Ukrainian hosting provider, but failed to uncover the identity of its operators.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In March 2024, the Rotterdam District Court ordered major ISPs in the Netherlands to block Anna's Archive and LibGen due to a request by advocacy group BREIN.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The order was "dynamic", meaning that if the blocked sites changed domains or IP addresses in the future, ISPs would be obligated to update their blocks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In December 2024, the UK Publishers Association won an order from the High Court of Justice requiring major ISPs to block Anna's Archive and other copyright-infringing sites, extending a list of sites blocked since 2015 under section 97A of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The Association said it identified over one million records of copyrighted books and journal articles on Anna's Archive domains.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The judge ordered FPS Economy's anti-piracy service to block the sites in the interim.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In the event of noncompliance, the sites face fines of up to 500,000 euros.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] On October 11, 2025, TorrentFreak reported that major ISPs in Germany had blocked access to the main domains of Anna's Archive.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The blockade was initiated by the Clearing Body for Copyright on the Internet (CUII), a coalition of rightsholders and ISPs that coordinates voluntary site blocking measures.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive was among Google Search's ten most reported domains for DMCA takedown by June 2024.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] By November 2025, Google had removed 749 million Anna's Archive URLs from its search results, representing 5 percent of all takedown requests sent to the search engine since 2012.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] These requests came from over 1,000 authors and publishers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] It has been one of the most targeted sites of Dutch anti-piracy service Link-Busters, which sends takedown requests to Google and other search engines on behalf of major publishers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] In January 2025, the messaging app Telegram suspended the Anna's Archive channel for copyright infringement, despite the operators reportedly taking precautions to avoid infringing posts on the app.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] Z-Library's Telegram channel was suspended the same week, and neither was alerted of the action.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/anna-s-archive] The removals were speculated to be linked to legal action by the Delhi High Court.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Arduino board designs use a variety of microprocessors and controllers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The boards are equipped with sets of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that may be interfaced to various expansion boards ('shields') or breadboards (for prototyping) and other circuits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The boards feature serial communications interfaces, including Universal Serial Bus (USB) on some models, which are also used for loading programs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The microcontrollers can be programmed using the C and C++ programming languages (Embedded C), using a standard API which is also known as the **Arduino Programming Language**, inspired by the Processing language and used with a modified version of the Processing IDE.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In addition to using traditional compiler toolchains, the Arduino project provides an integrated development environment (IDE) and a command line tool developed in Go.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino project began in 2005 as a tool for students at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea, Italy, aiming to provide a low-cost and easy way for novices and professionals to create devices that interact with their environment using sensors and actuators.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Common examples of such devices intended for makers include simple robots, thermostats, and motion detectors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The name *Arduino* comes from the Bar di Re Arduino, where some of the project's founders used to meet.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This bar is in Ivrea, Italy and was named after Arduin.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino project was started at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea (IDII) in Ivrea, Italy.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] At that time, the students used a BASIC Stamp microcontroller at a cost of $50.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In 2004, Hernando Barragán created the development platform *Wiring* as a Master's thesis project at IDII, under the supervision of Massimo Banzi and Casey Reas.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Casey Reas is known for co-creating, with Ben Fry, the Processing development platform.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The project goal was to create simple, low cost tools for creating digital projects by non-engineers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Wiring platform consisted of a printed circuit board (PCB) with an ATmega128 microcontroller, an IDE based on Processing and library functions to easily program the microcontroller.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In 2005, Massimo Banzi, with David Mellis, another IDII student, and David Cuartielles, extended Wiring by adding support for the cheaper ATmega8 microcontroller.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The new project, forked from Wiring, was called *Arduino*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The initial Arduino core team consisted of Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, Tom Igoe, Gianluca Martino, and David Mellis.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Following the completion of the platform, lighter and less expensive versions were distributed in the open-source community.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It was estimated in mid-2011 that over 300,000 official Arduinos had been commercially produced, and in 2013 that 700,000 official boards were in users' hands.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In early 2008, the five co-founders of the Arduino project created a company, Arduino LLC, to hold the trademarks associated with Arduino.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The manufacture and sale of the boards were to be done by external companies, and Arduino LLC would get a royalty from them.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The founding bylaws of Arduino LLC specified that each of the five founders transfer ownership of the Arduino brand to the newly formed company.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] At the end of 2008, Gianluca Martino's company, Smart Projects, registered the Arduino trademark in Italy and kept this a secret from the other co-founders for about two years.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This was revealed when the Arduino company tried to register the trademark in other areas of the world (they originally registered only in the US), and discovered that it was already registered in Italy.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Negotiations with Martino and his firm to bring the trademark under the control of the original Arduino company failed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In 2014, Smart Projects began refusing to pay royalties.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] They then appointed a new CEO, Federico Musto, who renamed the company *Arduino SRL* and created the website *arduino.org*, copying the graphics and layout of the original *arduino.cc*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This resulted in a rift in the Arduino development team.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In January 2015, Arduino LLC filed a lawsuit against Arduino SRL.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In May 2015, Arduino LLC created the worldwide trademark **Genuino**, used as brand name outside the United States.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] At the World Maker Faire in New York on 1 October 2016, Arduino LLC co-founder and CEO Massimo Banzi and Arduino SRL CEO Federico Musto announced the merger of the two companies, forming Arduino AG.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Around that same time, Massimo Banzi announced that in addition to the company a new Arduino Foundation would be launched as "a new beginning for Arduino", but this decision was withdrawn later.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In April 2017, Wired reported that Musto had "fabricated his academic record...
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] On his company's website, personal LinkedIn accounts, and even on Italian business documents, Musto was, until recently, listed as holding a Ph.D. from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In some cases, his biography also claimed an MBA from New York University." Wired reported that neither university had any record of Musto's attendance, and Musto later admitted in an interview with Wired that he had never earned those degrees.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The controversy surrounding Musto continued when, in July 2017, he reportedly pulled many open source licenses, schematics, and code from the Arduino website, prompting scrutiny and outcry.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] By 2017 Arduino 'AG' owned many Arduino trademarks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In July 2017 BCMI, founded by Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, David Mellis and Tom Igoe, acquired Arduino AG and all the Arduino trademarks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Fabio Violante is the new CEO replacing Federico Musto, who no longer works for Arduino AG.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In October 2017, Arduino announced its partnership with Arm Holdings (ARM).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The announcement said, in part, "ARM recognized independence as a core value of Arduino ... without any lock-in with the ARM architecture".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Arduino intends to continue to work with all technology vendors and architectures.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Under Violante's guidance, the company started growing again and releasing new designs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Genuino trademark was dismissed and all products were branded again with the Arduino name.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In August 2018, Arduino announced its new open source command line tool (arduino-cli), which can be used as a replacement of the IDE to program the boards from a shell.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In February 2019, Arduino announced its IoT Cloud service as an extension of the Create online environment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] As of February 2020, the Arduino community included about 30 million active users based on the IDE downloads.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In October 2025 it was announced that Arduino has been acquired, for an as yet undisclosed amount, by the American semiconductor multinational Qualcomm.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The hardware reference designs are distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.5 license and are available on the Arduino website.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Layout and production files for some versions of the hardware are also available.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Although the hardware and software designs are freely available under copyleft licenses, the developers have requested the name *Arduino* to be exclusive to the official product and not be used for derived works without permission.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The official policy document on the use of the Arduino name emphasizes that the project is open to incorporating work by others into the official product.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Several Arduino-compatible products commercially released have avoided the project name by using various names ending in *-duino*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Most Arduino boards consist of an Atmel 8-bit AVR microcontroller (ATmega8, ATmega168, ATmega328, ATmega1280, or ATmega2560) with varying amounts of flash memory, pins, and features.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The 32-bit Arduino Due, based on the Atmel SAM3X8E was introduced in 2012.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The boards use single or double-row pins or female headers that facilitate connections for programming and incorporation into other circuits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] These may connect with add-on modules termed *shields*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Multiple and possibly stacked shields may be individually addressable via an I²C serial bus.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Most boards include a 5 V linear regulator and a 16 MHz crystal oscillator or ceramic resonator.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some designs, such as the LilyPad, run at 8 MHz and dispense with the onboard voltage regulator due to specific form factor restrictions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Arduino microcontrollers are pre-programmed with a bootloader that simplifies the uploading of programs to the on-chip flash memory.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The default bootloader of the Arduino Uno is the Optiboot bootloader.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Boards are loaded with program code via a serial connection to another computer.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some serial Arduino boards contain a level shifter circuit to convert between RS-232 logic levels and transistor–transistor logic (TTL serial) level signals.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Current Arduino boards are programmed via Universal Serial Bus (USB), implemented using USB-to-serial adapter chips such as the FTDI FT232.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some boards, such as later-model Uno boards, substitute the FTDI chip with a separate AVR chip containing USB-to-serial firmware, which is reprogrammable via its own ICSP header.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Other variants, such as the Arduino Mini and the unofficial Boarduino, use a detachable USB-to-serial adapter board or cable, Bluetooth or other methods.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] When used with traditional microcontroller tools, instead of the Arduino IDE, standard AVR in-system programming (ISP) programming is used.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino board exposes most of the microcontroller's I/O pins for use by other circuits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The *Diecimila*, *Duemilanove*, and current *Uno* provide 14 digital I/O pins, six of which can produce pulse-width modulated(PWM) signals, and six analog inputs, which can also be used as six digital I/O pins.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] These pins are on the top of the board, via female 0.1-inch (2.54 mm) headers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Several plug-in application shields are also commercially available.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino Nano and Arduino-compatible Bare Bones Board and Boarduino boards may provide male header pins on the underside of the board that can plug into solderless breadboards.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Many Arduino-compatible and Arduino-derived boards exist.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some are functionally equivalent to an Arduino and can be used interchangeably.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Many enhance the basic Arduino by adding output drivers, often for use in school-level education, to simplify making buggies and small robots.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Others are electrically equivalent, but change the form factor, sometimes retaining compatibility with shields, sometimes not.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some variants use different processors, of varying compatibility.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] In addition to hardware variations, open source libraries have been developed to support Arduino hardware in EDA tools.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] One such project provides KiCad schematic symbols and PCB footprints for Arduino modules, expansion boards, and connectors, making it easier for engineers to integrate Arduino into their designs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The original Arduino hardware was manufactured by the Italian company Smart Projects.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Some Arduino-branded boards have been designed by the American companies SparkFun Electronics and Adafruit Industries.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] As of 2016, 17 versions of the Arduino hardware have been commercially produced.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Arduino shields are add-on boards that stack onto Arduino mainboards to extend their functionality for specific tasks.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Common uses include controlling DC motors for a robot, for 3D printer, adding a LCD display, enabling Ethernet connectivity, providing GPS/ GNSS navigation and converting pin headers into Grove connectors.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Shields are typically designed and manufactured by third-party hardware companies, including SparkFun Electronics, Adafruit Industries, Seeed Studio, and Cytron Technologies, among others.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Several shields can also be made do it yourself (DIY).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] A program for Arduino hardware may be written in any programming language with compilers that produce binary machine code for the target processor.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Atmel provides a development environment for their 8-bit AVR and 32-bit ARM Cortex-M based microcontrollers: AVR Studio (older) and Atmel Studio (newer).
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) is a cross-platform application (for Microsoft Windows, macOS, and Linux) that is based on *Processing IDE* which is written in Java.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It uses the *Wiring* API as programming style and HAL.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It includes a code editor with features such as text cutting and pasting, searching and replacing text, automatic indenting, brace matching, and syntax highlighting, and provides simple *one-click* mechanisms to compile and upload programs to an Arduino board.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It also contains a message area, a text console, a toolbar with buttons for common functions and a hierarchy of operation menus.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The source code for the IDE is released under the GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino IDE supports the languages C and C++ using special rules of code structuring.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino IDE supplies a software library from the Wiring project, which provides many common input and output procedures.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] User-written code only requires two basic functions, for starting the sketch and the main program loop, that are compiled and linked with a program stub *main()* into an executable cyclic executive program with the GNU toolchain, also included with the IDE distribution.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino IDE employs the program *avrdude* to convert the executable code into a text file in hexadecimal encoding that is loaded into the Arduino board by a loader program in the board's firmware.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] An initial alpha preview of a new Arduino IDE was released on October 18, 2019, as Arduino Pro IDE.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The beta preview was released on March 1, 2021, renamed IDE 2.0.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] On September 14, 2022, the Arduino IDE 2.0 was officially released as stable.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The system still uses Arduino CLI (Command Line Interface), but improvements include a more professional development environment and autocompletion support.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The application frontend is based on the Eclipse Theia Open Source IDE.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] One important feature Arduino IDE 2.0 provides is the debugging feature.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It allows users to single-step, insert breakpoints or view memory.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Debugging requires a target chip with debug port and a debug probe.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The official Arduino Zero board can be debugged out of the box.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Other official Arduino SAMD21 boards require a separate SEGGER J-Link or Atmel-ICE.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] For a 3rd party board, debugging in Arduino IDE 2.0 is also possible as long as such board supports GDB, OPENOCD and has a debug probe.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Community has contributed debugging for ATMega328P based Arduino or CH32 RISC-V boards, etc.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] A *sketch* is a program written with the Arduino IDE.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Sketches are saved on the development computer as text files with the file extension **.ino**.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Arduino Software (IDE) pre-1.0 saved sketches with the extension **.pde**.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Most Arduino boards contain a light-emitting diode (LED) and a current-limiting resistor connected between pin 13 and ground, which is a convenient feature for many tests and program functions.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] A typical program used by beginners, akin to Hello, World!, is "blink", which repeatedly blinks the on-board LED integrated into the Arduino board.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This program uses the functions `pinMode()`, `digitalWrite()`, and `delay()`, which are provided by the internal libraries included in the IDE environment.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This program is usually loaded into a new Arduino board by the manufacturer.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The open-source nature of the Arduino project has facilitated the publication of many free software libraries that other developers use to augment their projects.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] There is a Xinu OS port for the ATmega328P (Arduino Uno and others with the same chip), which includes most of the basic features.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The source code of this version is freely available.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] There is also a threading tool, named Protothreads.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] Protothreads are described as "extremely lightweight stackless threads designed for severely memory constrained systems, such as small embedded systems or wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] There is a port of FreeRTOS for the Arduino.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] This is available from the Arduino Library Manager.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] It is compatible with a number of boards, including the Uno.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino project received an honorary mention in the Digital Communities category at the 2006 Prix Ars Electronica.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/arduino] The Arduino Engineering Kit won the Bett Award for "Higher Education or Further Education Digital Services" in 2020.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Other terms are also associated with the do-it-yourself biology community.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The terms **biohacking** and **wetware hacking** emphasize the connection to hacker culture and the hacker ethic.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The term hacker is used in the original sense of finding new and clever ways to do things.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The term biohacking is also used by the grinder body modification community, which is considered related but distinct from the do-it-yourself biology movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The term **biopunk** emphasizes the techno-progressive, political, and artistic elements of the movement.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The term "biohacking" as well as the concept of do-it-yourself biology has been known as early as 1988.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Biohacking entered the San Francisco programmer and maker communities as early as 2005, through simple demonstrations of basic experiments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] As DIYbio experiments became the focus of SuperHappyDevHouse hackers, the hobby gained additional momentum.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2005 Rob Carlson wrote in an article in *Wired*: "The era of garage biology is upon us.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Take a moment to buy yourself a lab on eBay." He then set up a garage lab the same year, working on a project he had previously worked at the Molecular Sciences Institute in Berkeley, California.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2008, the DIYbio organization was founded by Jason Bobe and Mackenzie Cowell and its first meeting held.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2010, Genspace opened the first community biology lab, Ten months later it was followed by BioCurious, and Victoria Makerspace.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Many other labs and organizations followed, including but not limited to Counter Culture Labs in Oakland, CA, Baltimore Underground Science Space in Baltimore, MD, TheLab in Los Angeles, CA, Denver Biolabs in Denver, CO, and SoundBio Lab in Seattle, WA.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] It has been estimated that in 2014 there have been 50 DIY biology labs around the world.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2016, the first conference to focus specifically on biohacking was announced to take place in September in Oakland, CA.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] DIY biology is projected to develop even more into structured systems that have built legitimacy and public trust, with a community behind it that can be scientifically credible.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The DIYbio movement seeks to revise the notion that one must be an academic with an advanced degree to make any significant contribution to the biology community.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] It allows large numbers of small organizations and individuals to participate in research and development, with spreading knowledge a higher priority than turning profits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The DIY Biology Movement revolves around the ideals of using non-establishment research in order to allow for the freedom of research by people who are not considered qualified by regulatory bodies.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In recent years, there are various DIY ways to live healthy and many of them also focuses on different simple ways to biohack mind, body, metabolism, and sleep.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The motivations for DIY biology include (but aren't limited to) lowered costs, entertainment, medicine, biohacking, life extension, and education.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Recent work combining open-source hardware of microcontrollers like the Arduino and RepRap 3-D printers, very low-cost scientific instruments have been developed.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Many organizations maintain a laboratory akin to a wet-lab makerspace, providing equipment and supplies for members.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Many organizations also run classes and provide training.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] For a fee (usually between $50 and $100), members can join some spaces and do experiments on their own.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] DIY biology laboratories often use online forums, social media, and websites to communicate with other laboratories and DIY Biology enthusiasts in order to share their research with other laboratory bodies and communities.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The DIY biology movement attempts to make available the tools and resources necessary for anyone, including non-professionals, to conduct biological engineering.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] One of the first pieces of open source laboratory equipment developed was the Dremelfuge by Irish biohacker Cathal Garvey, which uses a 3D printed tube holder attached to a Dremel rotary tool to spin tubes at high speeds, replacing often expensive centrifuges.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Many other devices like PCR machines have been recreated extensively.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In recent times, more complex devices have been created such as the OpenDrop digital microfluidics platform and the DIY NanoDrop both developed by GaudiLabs.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Opentrons makes open-source software, affordable lab robots, and got its start as a DIY biology collaboration at Genspace.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Incuvers makes telemetric chambers for cellular research that are affordable and allow for complete customizability of their environments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] OpenCell, a London-based biotech lab provider hosts regular biohackathons to help encourage more opensource development.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Most advocacy in biohacking is about the safety, accessibility and future legality of experimentation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] DIY Biology findings are unregulated for the most part and therefore are deemed trustworthy by Trust Architecture, which the laboratories founded.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Trust Architecture is a set of systems that make a source or laboratory credible using infrastructure.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Todd Kuiken of the Woodrow Wilson Center proposes that through safety and self-governance, DIY biologists won't be in need of regulation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Jo Zayner has proposed that safety is inherent in biohacking and that accessibility should be the foremost concern as there is large underrepresentation of social and ethnic minorities in biohacking.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Many biohacking projects revolve around the modification of life and molecular and genetic engineering.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Genetic Engineers are a subculture of biohackers as one of the most accessible forms of biohacking is through engineering microorganisms or plants.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Experiments can range from using plasmids to fluorescent bacteria, controlling gene expression using light in bacteria, even using CRISPR to engineer the genome of bacteria or yeast.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Restricted access to medical care and medicine has pushed biohackers to start experimenting in medically related fields.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The Open Insulin project aims to make the recombinant protein insulin more accessible by creating an open source protocol for expression and purification.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Other experiments that have involved medical treatments include a whole body microbiome transplant and the creation of open source artificial pancreases for diabetics, such as OpenAPS, Loop and AndroidAPS.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Other laboratory spaces created medical-grade face shields and other COVID-19 relief mechanisms in response to the pandemic.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Grinders are a subculture of biohackers that focus on implanting technology or introducing chemicals into the body to enhance or change their bodies' functionality.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Some biohackers can now sense which direction they face using a magnetic implant that vibrates against the skin.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2000, controversial and self-described "transgenic artist" Eduardo Kac appropriated standard laboratory work by biotechnology and genetics researchers in order to both utilize and critique such scientific techniques.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The claimed work came to be known as the "GFP bunny", and which Kac called *Alba*.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] The laboratory consequently kept possession of the transgenic rabbit which it had created and funded and the "transgenic art" was never exhibited at the Digital Avignon festival [2000] as intended.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Kac—claiming that his rabbit was the first GFP bunny created in the name of Art—used this dispute to popularize the issue as one of disguised censorship by launching a "Free Alba" campaign.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] A doctored photo of the artist holding a day-glow-green tinted rabbit appears on his website.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Heather Dewey-Hagborg is an information artist and biohacker who uses genomic DNA left behind by people as a starting point for creating lifelike, computer-generated, 3-D portraits.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Biohacking experiences many of the same criticisms as synthetic biology and genetic engineering already receive, plus other concerns relating to the distributed and non-institutional nature of the work, involving potential hazards with lack of oversight by professionals or governments.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Concerns about biohackers creating pathogens in unmonitored garage laboratories led the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) to begin sending its representatives to DIYbio conferences in 2009.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] At the National Institutes of Health, National Science Advisory Board for Biosecurity leads efforts to educate the public on "dual use research of concern", for example with websites like "Science Safety Security".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In 2011, DIYbio organized conferences to attempt to create codes of ethics for biohackers.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] A 2007 ETC Group report warns that the danger of this development is not just bioterror, but "bio-error".
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Further regulation into research conducted by these DIY Biology laboratories could lead them to being able to produce government-backed data.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] However, the movement was founded on the core ideals of unregulated biological innovations.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] In order to keep these laboratories accountable, Trust Architecture and regulatory bodies are implemented in the community to ensure accountability.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] DIYbio argues that fear of potential hazards should be met with increased research and education rather than closing the door on the profound positive impacts that distributed biological technology will have on human health, the environment, and the standard of living around the world.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Due to the lack of precedent regarding such a business model, the DIYbio founders see this as an opportunity to be innovators in regulatory and safety policy.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] Given the ongoing controversy surrounding biosafety, one of the ways people can become more aware of how to incorporate safety is through understanding which levels of experimentation require regulation.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] According to the National Institute of Health guidelines for research involving recombinant DNA, experiments are categorized based on their potential risk, with higher-risk work, such as manipulating pathogenic organisms.
[src:do-it-yourself-biology/do-it-yourself-biology] While lower-risk activities, such as basic laboratory techniques that do not involve harmful agents, may be exempt or require minimal oversight.
